<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-01-16T22:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-01-16T22:00:00-05:00" n="36" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d36">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/3542: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName corresp="#p_JNT1" type="from">Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-01-17T11:00:00+08:00">January 17, 1932—11
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received January 17—3:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>82. Following from American Consul General at Mukden: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“January 16, 1 p.m. Telegram No. 32. Headquarters reports that a
                                    Japanese battalion occupied Tungliao January 14, noon, after
                                    ejecting 3,000 Chinese partisans; losses, Chinese 60, Japanese
                                    0.</p>
                                <p>Reliable information is to the effect that these so-called
                                    partisans belonged to the Third Cavalry Brigade of which about
                                    1,000 were in Tungliao.”</p></quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="#p_JNT1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>